 	<div id="main-article-info">

		
		
			<h1 itemprop="name headline  "
								>Great moments in science (if Twitter had existed)</h1>
		
					<div itemprop="description" id="stand-first"
				 class="stand-first-alone"                        	        data-component="Article:standfirst_cta"			><p>Twitter is the source of a great deal of modern news, and scientists are often encouraged to tweet about their research. So what if Twitter had been around during the times of historic scientific breakthroughs and discoveries? </p></div>
		
		
  	</div>

  	  	    			<ul id="content-actions" class="share-links trackable-component"         	        data-component="Article:top share tools">
				                
    
	
		
												


    
    
    	
    	
    	

        <li class="full-line facebook">
        <span class="facebook-share">
            <a class="facebook-share-btn" href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http://www.theguardian.com/science/brain-flapping/2014/jul/21/famous-science-history-twitter-humour" data-href="http://www.theguardian.com/science/brain-flapping/2014/jul/21/famous-science-history-twitter-humour" data-link-name="Facebook Share Top">
                <span class="facebook-share-icon"></span>
                <span class="facebook-share-label">Share</span>
            </a>
        </span>
    </li>

    <li class="full-line" data-link-name="Twitter Top">
	    	    	    	    	    	    <a href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-url="http://gu.com/p/4v52f/tw" data-via="guardian" data-counturl="http://www.theguardian.com/science/brain-flapping/2014/jul/21/famous-science-history-twitter-humour" data-related="guardianscience" data-text="Great moments in Science (if Twitter had existed) | Dean Burnett">Tweet this</a>
